<?xml version="1.0"?><collection name="D0835-A"><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>Players would be under oath and risk perjury if lying in testimony, so they face a hot seat if asked whether or not they took steroids.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0624"><line>The Anabolic Steroid Control Act would add androstenedione, norandrosterone and similar testosterone-production enhancing substances to a list of anabolic steroids regarded as controlled substances.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>Being clean now that tests are ongoing is no sign of purity in past years and the reduced size of several past top hitters nags at skeptics.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>Earlier this year it was agreed -- in the middle of a collective bargaining agreement -- to extend that program significantly.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050224.0679"><line>A first positive test would now result in a suspension of up to 10 days, a second positive test a 30-day ban, a third positive a 60-day penalty.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>All have denied any wrongdoing but the stigma of the accusation in the wake of the BALCO steroid scandal revelations and the lack of steroid testing prior to 2004 in the major leagues has cast suspicion over numerous 1990s stars.</line><line>&quot;You can't control what people are going to write and say,&quot; Yankees star Derek Jeter said of Giambi's situation.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>It laid out in considerable detail the known effects of various classes of performance-enhancing drugs.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>My muscles got too strong for my tendons and ligaments.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>Bonds said last week he would testify if his attorney thought it was a good idea.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>He said the steroid use was catching up to him.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="43,5"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0624"><line>After between five and seven percent of players tested positive in anonymous testing last year, a tougher testing programme was installed, although global sports officials have called relatively light penalties by Olympic standards laughable.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="55"><scu uid="38" label="MLB's recently toughened penalties are far below international anti-doping standards" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041115.0562"><line>Bonds, fourth in homers with 45, led the NL in batting (.362), on-base percentage (.609) and was second in runs scored with 129.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>Bonds, 38, is approaching the all-time home run record of 755 by Hank Aaron.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>Former National Football League star Lyle Alzado attributed excessive steroid use to the brain cancer that killed him.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="40"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0170"><line>That program was criticized as too lenient.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>Before the mid-1990s, the substances of choice in the clubhouse were amphetamines and recreational drugs.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0808"><line>&quot;We have a number of questions about the discrepancies between Major League Baseball's public presentation of its new drug testing effort and the language of the new policy.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>At the time, many anabolic steroids were illegal if purchased without a prescription.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>Alderson, general manager of the Oakland A's during the era when Canseco was powering them into the playoffs. supported the idea that Canseco was seeking attention for his book and other moneymaking projects.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041115.0562"><line>His 120 intentional walks were 52 beyond the old record.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0170"><line>Responding to criticism that Major League Baseball has not done enough to deter steroid use among players, Commissioner Bud Selig said in a telephone interview Friday that the testing program put in place two years ago showed a significant drop in positive tests in 2004.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="11" sums="11,16,23,25,30,36,41,44,5,51,55"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>You know what that's like?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0170"><line>&quot;However, I think the 1 to 2 percent shows that the steps we have taken have allowed the game to make progress.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0808"><line>Major League Baseball, which presented its plan to lawmakers Monday in advance of the hearings, began steroid testing last season and unveiled a toughened plan January 13 that Selig said &quot;will eradicate steroid use.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="37,6"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050224.0679"><line>&quot;There is a simple way to find the truth in this matter.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>Sosa and McGwire were involved in an epic homer race in 1998 where both surpassed the old homer record, one that helped revive interest in the sport.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>The problem is that there is no evidence because of the lack of a testing program.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0808"><line>&quot;There appear to be major differences between Major League Baseball's new policy and the independent, widely respected testing program of the Olympics.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>&quot;We have made an offer (to make witnesses available) that should be sufficient to answer any questions about what has gone on with regard to Major League Baseball and steroids.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0624"><line>US lawmakers passed legislation allowing tighter government regulation of steroid precursors here Monday, one day after the death of former baseball star Ken Caminiti, an admitted steroid user.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="2" sums="20,29"><scu uid="39" label="The new Anabolic Steroid Control Act makes steroid precursors controlled substances" weight="4"/><scu uid="4" label="Major League Baseball player Ken Caminiti admitted taking steroids" weight="3"/><scu uid="27" label="Baseball star Ken Caminiti died" weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>&quot;This important legislation will help us reach our goal of zero tolerance in the battle against steroids,&quot; major league commissioner Bud Selig said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>Caminiti said he used steroids for about eight years after injuring his shoulder as a member of the San Diego Padres.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>It would be equally easy to argue that baseball might have acted sooner or more punitively.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>&quot;I've heard people say over and over that the owners liked it and the players liked it and it brought money in,&quot; Selig said.</line><line>&quot;There's a great deal of suspicion on the part of fans,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050224.0679"><line>&quot;Jose Canseco's allegations about steroid use by Mark McGwire and other baseball players have received enormous media attention.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="13,29,55"><scu uid="5" label="Major League Baseball player Mark McGwire admitted taking steroids" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0808"><line>US lawmakers ripped into Major League Baseball's new drug testing plan, describing it as shamefully inadequate on the eve of a Congressional hearing into rampant steroid taking by stars.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="9" sums="0,23,25,37,48,49,51,6,7"><scu uid="40" label="Congress investigated steroid use in Major League Baseball" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041203.0044"><line>Bonds testified that he thought the substances, believed to be the previously undetectable steroid THG, were a rubbing balm for arthritis and nutritional supplement flaxseed oil.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>He, who played for Los Angeles, Denver and Cleveland, insisted that almost 20 years of steroid use was the major contributing factor.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="38,8"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>The next year, together with the players union, baseball helped finance a study on androstenedione.</line><line>In the same year, it decided to put in a stringent testing and penalty program for the minor leagues.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>&quot;This is not about one individual,&quot; Kucinich said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>In June 2001, Major League Baseball published a pamphlet in English and in Spanish and distributed it to major league and minor league players.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050224.0679"><line>In a letter to Tom Davis, chairman of the House Government Reform Committee, Waxman said he also wants MLB officials to explain what measures they are taking to deal with the steroids.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0170"><line>Selig was reacting to concerns that baseball's steroid testing program was not tough enough.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041203.0044"><line>Baseball star slugger Barry Bonds told a grand jury that he used a clear substance and cream from a firm embroiled in a doping scandal, but he never thought they were steroids, the San Francisco Chronicle reported Thursday.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>But it is also proper to remember that baseball was hampered by the confidentiality of doctor-patient relationships, the sanctity of the clubhouse culture and union concerns about privacy rights.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>&quot;Consistent with our jurisdiction over the nation's drug policy, we need to better understand the steps MLB is taking to get a handle on the steroid issue and whether news of those steps and the danger posed by steroid use, is reaching America's youth.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>Caminiti's best season was 1996 when, at age 33, he hit 40 homers had 130 runs batted in and a.326 batting average.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>Bonds owns the major league one-season home run record and could eclipse Hank Aaron's career homer record in 2006, but Bonds' BALCO link and baseball's lack of steroid testing for key years in his career have clouded the feat.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="21,3,35"><scu uid="7" label="Players suspected of steroid use include Barry Bonds" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>That report came from Kimberly Bell, who says she was Bonds' mistress for nine years and that he admitted using steroids in 1999 and 2000.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041203.0044"><line>Bonds hit a single-season record 73 home runs in 2001 and has a career total of 703 homers - 53 shy of breaking Hank Aaron's all-time American homer record.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="33"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>Giambi is set to play for the Yankees as part of his seven-year contract worth 120 million dollars but faces the new accusation as he prepares for a new season.</line><line>&quot;The guys who were named will have to answer questions every day of spring training and will always have that allegation hanging over them.&quot;</line><line>Selig said if Bonds becomes the all-time homer king, his mark would be hailed as any other despite the shadow of doping looming over recent acheivements.</line><line>Weak penalties were toughened for the upcoming season but remain far below the two-year ban imposed under World Anti-Doping Agency rules.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041203.0044"><line>Anderson, BALCO founder Victor Conte, BALCO executive James Valente and athletics coach Remy Korchemny are all charged with steroid distribution.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="21,57"><scu uid="33" label="The BALCO steroid distribution scandal indicates rampant steroid use in MLB" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>Former major league slugger Jose Canseco's new book &quot;Juiced: Wild Times, Rampant 'Roids, Smash Hits and How Baseball Got Big&quot; includes claims he injected steroids into several of baseball's biggest, literally, stars.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="43"><scu uid="31" label="Former MLB player revelations indicate rampant steroid use" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>Incidentally, it wasn't until May 2002 that Ken Caminiti, in an interview with Sports Illustrated, estimated that half of major leaguers were using steroids.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0170"><line>Selig said baseball had researched and studied androstenedione, initiated a minor league testing program, urged Congress to ban over-the-counter sales of steroid precursors and made steroids a priority in negotiations for a new collective bargaining agreement.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="12,42"><scu uid="17" label="Commissioner Bud Selig urged banning over-the-counter sales of steroids" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0808"><line>First offences were stated as punishable by &quot;a 10-day suspension or up to a 10,000-dollar fine&quot; with second offences a 30-day ban or 25,000-dollar fine, then 60-day ban or 50,000-dollar fine, one-year ban or 100,000-dollar fine.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>It turned out to be the seminal study on the substance and was later published in a leading medical journal.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>&quot;We need to look at the overall effect.&quot;</line><line>&quot;It should be about lifting baseball up out of this cloud - no witch hunts, no intention to force somebody into a position where they will be prosecuted,&quot; committee member Dennis Kucinich told ESPN.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>He was 41.</line><line>&quot;My tendons and ligaments got all torn up.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>Commissioner Bud Selig and Major League Baseball have taken a lot of heat over the last several months for their supposed failure to grapple forthrightly with the sport's steroid problem.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050224.0679"><line>Our committee should hold a hearing with Mr Canseco, Mr McGwire and others and have them testify under oath.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>Bell has said she intends to write a book on the subject.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>Manfred objected to the subpoenas, saying, &quot;It is singularly inapporiate to subpoena certain players&quot; because it would tarnish their reputations.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0170"><line>At a news conference in Mesa, Ariz., on Saturday, Selig would not say whether he would appear before the committee.</line><line>In international track and field, a first-time offender is out for two years.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>Major League Baseball must be patient and tenacious if it is to have success in the long-run fight against performance-enhancing drugs.</line><line>Baseball reasoned that if it could get players to the majors clean, then it had won half the battle.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="10"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0808"><line>US Senator John McCain ripped Selig and Fehr in a letter for misrepresenting the standards of baseball's anti-doping plan and hinted that lawmakers were ready to take action if baseball leaders would not impose mandatory bans.</line><line>In a joint statement, Major League Baseball confirmed only that the draft given Monday to lawmakers was indeed the plan being used since March 3.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>Bonds' personal trainer, Greg Anderson, is among four men charged in a steroid distribution ring in the BALCO case.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>I broke down a lot,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050224.0679"><line>In his controversial new book, &quot;Juiced: Wild Times, Rampant 'Roids, Smash Hits and How Baseball Got Big,&quot; Canseco said he injected steroids into some of the baseball's biggest stars, including home run legend McGwire and New York Yankees superstar Jason Giambi.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>&quot;I'm not going to comment on a book I haven't read or seen.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>The prevailing view was that top offensive performances in baseball demanded quick reflexes, good eye-hand coordination, quick feet, flexibility and strong wrists -- not bulky muscles.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0808"><line>Steroid offenders who are fined rather than suspended are not identified under baseball's plan and even those suspended have no mandatory public confirmation the ban was for steroids, results being &quot;strictly confidential&quot;.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>&quot;The remaining witnesses, however, made it clear - either by flatly rejecting the invitation to testify or by ignoring our repeated attempts to contact them - they had no intention of appearing before the committee.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041115.0562"><line>Bonds, who hit his 700th career homer in September, received 24 of 32 first-place votes and 407 points overall in balloting by writers to claim his fourth consecutive league MVP honor.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0808"><line>The baseball policy excludes four anabolic steroids - boldione, danazol, quinbolone and dihydroepiandrostone - that are banned for Olympians.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>Caminiti is the latest athlete to die at a young age after admitting to using performance enhancing drugs.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="32"><scu uid="4" label="Major League Baseball player Ken Caminiti admitted taking steroids" weight="3"/><scu uid="27" label="Baseball star Ken Caminiti died" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0170"><line>And in the minor league steroid testing program, which began in 2001, Selig said positive results had gone from 11 percent in 2001 to 4.8 percent in 2002 to 4.0 percent in 2003 to 1.7 percent last year.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>Some have even suggested that people in the commissioner's office have been winking at one another while they make public pronouncements against steroid use.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>Lawmakers have stressed sending a message to American youth about the harmful nature of taking steroids, something US President George W. Bush mentioned 14 months ago in a State of the Union speech.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0170"><line>&quot;This year I believe we will clean that up,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>Barry Bonds, the superstar most nagged by steroid accusations, was not given the chance to clear his name as he was not invited or subpoenaed.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050224.0679"><line>Democratic lawmaker Henry Waxman of California asked Thursday that former baseball star Jose Canseco appear at congressional hearings to talk about the steroid scandal.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="4" sums="11,14,41,57"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>It should not be a witch hunt.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0808"><line>&quot;According to experts, hundreds of potential &quot;designer&quot; steroids already exist.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0170"><line>Even the penalties under baseball's latest plan are light compared with those of other sports.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050224.0679"><line>Waxman said the steroid issue not only threatens the health of professional players but also youths who feel the only way to be successful in the sport is to take steroids.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>&quot;It's so without merit that you wonder how people can even talk about it.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>The dimensions and the implications of the drug issue in professional sports are just beginning to be understood.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>Baseball executives and union leaders have agreed to toughen penalties for this season after imposing the first steroid tests last season.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="19"><scu uid="14" label="Baseball executives have agreed to toughen penalties " weight="1"/><scu uid="15" label="Baseball players union leaders have agreed to toughen penalties " weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>It's terrible.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>&quot;I think there's something to that,&quot; Alderson said, adding that &quot;it doesn't seem he's making any effort to make any progress&quot; in combating steroids in baseball.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>&quot;If you bring Bonds up, he's going to be the whole show at this point,&quot; committee chairman Tom Davis told ESPN, saying he hoped to avoid a &quot;witch hunt&quot;.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0170"><line>&quot;The average player would lose $140,000 if he is suspended for 10 days.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0808"><line>Revealing weak points of the plan, US House of Representatives Government Reform Committee chairman Tom Davis and ranking minority member Henry Waxman sent an open letter to baseball commissioner Bud Selig and union boss Don Fehr.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="0,7"/></line><line>&quot;Our preliminary review raises questions about whether the new policy is as comprehensive and effective as... claimed,&quot; Davis and Waxman wrote, pointing up numerous weaknesses compared with World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) standards.</line><line>&quot;The Olympic policy appears comprehensive, strict, independent, and transparent.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041115.0562"><line>The 40-year-old slugger, poised to challenge the all-time home run record, won the award for the fourth year in a row and seventh time overall.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>&quot;At least half the guys are using (steroids).</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>It is a safe bet that today Selig and others wish they had done more earlier.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>Tony La Russa, manager of the A's during Canseco's era and now manager of the reigning National League champion St. Louis Cardinals, predicted a bad fate for Canseco.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>Underscoring the intractability of the problem is the fact that most athletes under investigation in the BALCO scandal are Olympians, and that the International Olympic Committee is reputed to have the gold standard in anti-doping policies.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0624"><line>A bill to amend the Controlled Substances Act, toughening penalties for anabolic steroid offenses near sports facilities, was put forth on March 1 and passed by the US House of Representatives in June.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="19"><scu uid="37" label="If the League does not impose mandatory bans lawmakers will consider stronger action" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050224.0679"><line>Baseball has been trying in the last few months to toughen its penalties for steroid use but critics say the new laws lag behind other sports.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0624"><line>Drug testing was a key part of the labor deal baseball club owners signed with players in 2002.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>But as baseball became more aware of this as a growing issue, the commissioner's office did, in fact, act.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>The much travelled Caminiti played for Atlanta, Houston, San Diego and Texas.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0808"><line>&quot;I expect the league and the players' union to modify the new policy.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0624"><line>The legislation allows the US Drug Enforcement Agency to regulate these products as anabolic steroids under the Controlled Substances Act.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>You get lethargic.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041203.0044"><line>All have pleaded not guilty.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>&quot;It's no secret what's going on in baseball,&quot; said Caminiti, who retired in 2001 after 15 years in the major leagues.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0170"><line>A House committee has announced it will investigate steroid use in baseball, and Selig has been invited to testify along with a number of present and former players, among them Jose Canseco and Mark McGwire.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="5,55"><scu uid="40" label="Congress investigated steroid use in Major League Baseball" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>Caminiti is just the latest professional athlete to die after admitting steroid use.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="5"><scu uid="4" label="Major League Baseball player Ken Caminiti admitted taking steroids" weight="3"/><scu uid="27" label="Baseball star Ken Caminiti died" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>Adding to the steroid chaos was a report on Fox News Channel that Barry Bonds, who has admitted taking BALCO products but said he was unaware they were steroids, knowingly used steroids and was fearful of being discovered.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="22"><scu uid="7" label="Players suspected of steroid use include Barry Bonds" weight="2"/><scu uid="33" label="The BALCO steroid distribution scandal indicates rampant steroid use in MLB" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>Indeed, it was probably around 10 years ago that some people in baseball became aware that anabolic steroids were being used by some players.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="22,48"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050224.0679"><line>Under the previous agreement, a first positive test resulted only in treatment.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0808"><line>&quot;The failure of Major League Baseball to cover designer steroids would appear to be a significant omission,&quot; Davis and Waxman wrote.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>&quot;He'll be a pariah in baseball,&quot; La Russa said.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="18"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0808"><line>&quot;Designer&quot; steroids covered under Olympic doping guidelines are not under baseball's plan.</line><line>We hope you will come prepared to address these questions.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>&quot;I don't think it was the right thing to do,&quot; Yankees star Tino Martinez said of the book.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0170"><line>Selig defended baseball's record in trying to clear up the steroid problem, saying he had devoted the last seven years dealing with it since learning in 1998 that McGwire used the supplement androstenedione.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>Canseco admitted using steroids himself throughout a 16-year career in which they were not banned by Major League Baseball.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="4" sums="22,32,37,44"><scu uid="6" label="Major League Baseball player Jose Canseco admitted taking steroids" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0808"><line>Major League Baseball is still confronting a major scandal cgation is launched into drug testing and the league and union &quot;have successfully resisted an investigation at the trial court level&quot; with the entire program subject to renegotiation if suspended beyond a year.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041203.0044"><line>The report said that Bonds, testifying on December 4 of last year, told a federal grand jury investigating the BALCO steroid scandal that he received and used &quot;clear&quot; and cream substances obtained from personal trainer Greg Anderson.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0170"><line>&quot;One person from our perspective is too much,&quot; he said in a telephone interview.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050224.0679"><line>Mr Canseco insists his information is accurate,&quot; Waxman said.</line><line>&quot;We should also hear from representatives from Major League Baseball and the players' union to examine what they plan to do to stop the use of dangerous drugs by pro baseball players.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="36"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>&quot;There's really not the proof out there to make this possible,&quot; Alderson said Monday, noting that more and more fans are unhappy.</line><line>&quot;You just take care of what you can control.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>It also hired a new medical staff to advise it on drug policy.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0170"><line>The tests were conducted under an agreement between the players and management in 2002.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>They joke about it with each other.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050224.0679"><line>The players have vehemently denied ever using performance-enhancing steroids.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>&quot;It's important the American people know the facts on baseball's steroid scandal and it's important all Americans, especially children, know about the dangers of drug use,&quot; Davis said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>They would benefit from taking a step back and looking more carefully at the evolution of the steroid problem in baseball.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0170"><line>Selig said the results refuted &quot;the thought that this is running wild.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>It would be easy to go back and identify instances when baseball might have gotten the message sooner.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>Several players had said they would not attend the hearing.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>As Sandy Alderson, Major League Baseball's vice president of baseball operations, told ESPN, there is likely no way McGwire can distance himself from Canseco's claims despite his repeated denials of taking performance enhancers.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0808"><line>The penalty for a fifth violation is at the commissioner's discretion.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041115.0562"><line>Willie Stargell was the previous oldest to win the award, doing so in 1979 at age 39.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050224.0679"><line>Many of the individuals have denied the accusations.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>&quot;Breaking records will be celebrated like all records will be celebrated,&quot; Selig said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0808"><line>&quot;Despite the public assurances of Major League Baseball officials, we have questions about the effectiveness of its new drug policy,&quot; Davis and Waxman wrote.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>Selig was irate at the notion that major league owners and players profited from blind eyes to steroid takers because they boosted crowds and helped erase long-term labor woes that included wiping out the 1994 World Series.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>Eradicating drug abuse is no simple matter.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>It should be about looking at the issue, raising the discussion.</line><line>Manfred said.</line><line>Curt Schilling, Frank Thomas and Rafael Palmeiro also were ordered to speak March 17 to a House of Representatives Government Reform Committee hearing in a session that could blow the lid off Major League Baseball's steroid scandal.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0170"><line>Selig said 1 to 2 percent of players in the major league program tested positive last year, down from 5 to 7 percent in 2003.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="43"><scu uid="20" label="One to two percent of players tested positive in 2005" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041115.0562"><line>Los Angeles Dodgers third baseman Adrian Beltre was second, 96 points back with six first-place votes, and St. Louis slugger Albert Pujols was third with one first-place vote and 247 points.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0624"><line>He had admitted to using steroids during his Most Valuable Player season in 1996, when he hit.326 with 40 homers and 130 runs batted in for the San Diego Padres.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>Indeed, the new testing and penalty protocol is far from perfect.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041203.0044"><line>A trial is expected to start in March.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>Asked if general managers should question the players mentioned in the book, Alderson said, &quot;Is it up to a general manager to ask if a player is cheating on his wife?&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>&quot;I got really strong, really quick.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0624"><line>BALCO founder Victor Conte and vice president James Valente, athletics coach Remi Korchemny and Greg Anderson, the personal trainer for baseball star Barry Bonds, have all pleaded not guilty to steroid distribution charges in the case.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="20"><scu uid="33" label="The BALCO steroid distribution scandal indicates rampant steroid use in MLB" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041115.0562"><line>Bonds had steadfastly denied any wrongdoing.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0808"><line>Compare that to the two-year public ban for steroid first offenders in Olympic sports and lifetime ban thereafter under WADA rules and it's easy to see why baseball's plan was eyed with scorn and skepticism.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041115.0562"><line>Bonds set a major league record with 232 walks, more than 100 more than the next closest player.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0170"><line>Rob Manfred, baseball's chief labor relations executive, said he was also encouraged by the 2004 major league results.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0624"><line>js/gph04</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>Steroid controversy swirled around Major League Baseball here Monday as a new book with doping accusations hit the stands and players began pre-season training in Florida.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="7" sums="23,25,29,30,49,51,55"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>&quot;And now my body's not producing testosterone.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041115.0562"><line>With 703 career homers, Bonds trails only Hank Aaron's record 755 and Babe Ruth's 714 on the all-time homers list.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0170"><line>&quot;I often hear it's a weak program,&quot; Selig said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>Canseco claimed to inject steroids into former one-season home run record setter Mark McGwire, New York Yankees star Jason Giambi plus Rafael Palmeiro, Ivan Rodriguez and Juan Gonzalez when they were teammates in Texas and Oakland.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="19,48"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>From my perspective, these critics are jumping to unfair conclusions.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>&quot;I don't want to talk about Canseco's book,&quot; Major League Baseball commissioner Bud Selig said Monday.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0808"><line>&quot;One hundred thousand dollars is less money than some players earn in one game,&quot; Davis and Waxman noted.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>Former Major League Baseball all-star Ken Caminiti, who admitted taking steroids to boost his playing career, died of a heart attack on Sunday.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="4" sums="14,33,40,49"><scu uid="4" label="Major League Baseball player Ken Caminiti admitted taking steroids" weight="3"/><scu uid="27" label="Baseball star Ken Caminiti died" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>All have pleaded innocent.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>&quot;I'm not going to comment on anecdotal evidence or no evidence at all.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050224.0679"><line>&quot;Despite the baseball commissioner's statement that his goal is to have zero tolerance regarding steroids, Major League Baseball has announced it will not investigate Mr. Canseco's allegations.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>&quot;Jose Canseco, Donald Fehr and Rob Manfred have already told the committee they will testify,&quot; Davis said.</line><line>Also issued subpoenas were Robert Manfred, Major League Baseball executive vice president; players union executive director Don Fehr; San Diego Padres general manager Kevin Towers and former Oakland general manager Sandy Alderson, now Major League Baseball's vice president of baseball operations.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="5" sums="21,3,35,38,8"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>gph04</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>Also Monday, USA Today reported that the Yankees admitted removing the word &quot;steroid&quot; from Giambi's contract during 2001 talks, saying they felt they were protected on the issue by broader language elsewhere in the deal that banned &quot;illegal drugs&quot; or &quot;chemical use and dependency.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0170"><line>If about 1,200 players were tested in 2004, then 12 to 24 tested positive.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>Baseball implemented recent changes to its drug testing policies which critics have called too lax.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>They could say yes or no or refuse to answer for self-incrimination, a practical guilt admission.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>Alzado, who played from 1971-85, died at 43 on May 14, 1992.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050224.0679"><line>In the Olympics the first penalty is a two-year ban.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>But a 10-day ban for first-time offenders, 30 days for second offenses and 60 days for third-time cheaters is still far shy of two-year bans for Olympic sports - a tougher level of testing that does not govern US sports leagues.</line><line>San Francisco Giants star Bonds admitted taking products that have been identified by prosecutors as steroids as part of the BALCO doping scandal.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0624"><line>As with athletics, baseball has been criticized since the BALCO Labs steroid scandal broke a year ago.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="13,43"><scu uid="33" label="The BALCO steroid distribution scandal indicates rampant steroid use in MLB" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>The 30-team league only began a ban last year.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line><line>Bonds' lawyer admits the ballplayer had a relationship with Bell but said the steroid claims are to promote the book and come after failed attempts to collect money from Bonds.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>An FBI special agent, Greg Stejskal, told the news media last month that he had notified Major League Baseball about 10 years ago that steroid use was a developing problem.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="10,44"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041203.0044"><line>On its website, the newspaper cited a transcript of Bonds' testimony to support a claim that would forever taint the 40-year-old Major League Baseball star's historic home run feats.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="33"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>New chemical compounds and new delivery methods (making detection much more difficult) are being developed every day.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0808"><line>Major League Baseball's program appears to raise questions on all four counts.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>Canseco's new book &quot;Juiced: Wild Times, Rampant 'Roids, Smash Hits and How Baseball Got Big&quot; named several top stars as steroid users, including retired St. Louis star McGwire, New York Yankees star Giambi and Palmeiro, a Baltimore teammate of Dominican standout Sosa.</line><line>An off-season testing program has been started.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line><line>&quot;The hearings have to be conducted in a way that is not prosecutory.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>Down the road, gene-modification therapy will further complicate the landscape.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041115.0562"><line>Major League Baseball did not institute a full steroid-testing program until this season, but a steroid previously undetectable by testing was at the heart of the BALCO case.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0170"><line>Another huge deterrent is naming people.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>Steroid-tainted baseball stars Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa, Jason Giambi and Jose Canseco were among 11 people issued subpoenas here Wednesday to testify next week before a US Congress hearing on steroids.<annotation scu-count="5" sum-count="2" sums="16,57"><scu uid="5" label="Major League Baseball player Mark McGwire admitted taking steroids" weight="3"/><scu uid="6" label="Major League Baseball player Jose Canseco admitted taking steroids" weight="3"/><scu uid="1" label="Congress held hearings on baseball steroid use" weight="2"/><scu uid="8" label="Players suspected of steroid use include Sammy Sosa" weight="2"/><scu uid="9" label="Players suspected of steroid use include Jason Giambi" weight="2"/></annotation></line><line>Now they must do so or face contempt citations.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>In 2002, baseball and the union agreed to their first steroid testing and penalty program.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="18,49"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0808"><line>The option of imposing fines rather than mandatory bans for steroid offenses raised questions about the quality of MLB's anti-doping plan as well as the trustworthiness of leaders to police the game.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="0,7"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0624"><line>Grand jury testimony saw many top sports figures testify, including San Francisco star Bonds and Gary Sheffield and Jason Giambi of the New York Yankees.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>You get depressed.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>Fans, too, need patience.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041115.0562"><line>San Francisco's Barry Bonds, whose Major League Baseball feats have been dogged by unproven steroid suspicions, became the oldest player to win the National League Most Valuable Player award on Monday.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="7" sums="11,12,14,29,30,41,42"><scu uid="7" label="Players suspected of steroid use include Barry Bonds" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>I pulled a lot of muscles.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0170"><line>A first-time offender draws a 10-day suspension.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050224.0679"><line>Waxman would also like to call Canseco's former teammate Mark McGwire and force them to testify under oath about the culture of performance-enhancing drugs in Major League Baseball (MLB).<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="6"><scu uid="5" label="Major League Baseball player Mark McGwire admitted taking steroids" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>Caminiti become the first American baseball player to publicly admit using steroids in 2002.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="5" sums="10,22,37,40,6"><scu uid="4" label="Major League Baseball player Ken Caminiti admitted taking steroids" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>But a major sponsor pulled out promotional plans in the wake of steroid revelations about Bonds.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="48"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0808"><line>&quot;We expect player ratification within days,&quot; Fehr said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0624"><line>&quot;This will allow us to test for steroid precursors, just as we are currently testing for steroids, as part of our regular testing.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>The ex-MVP of the National League in 1996 and gold glove winner was selected to the all-star team three times.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>One must understand the scope of the problem before one can devise effective policy.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0808"><line>&quot;This provision appears designed to discourage responsible independent oversight,&quot; Davis and Waxman wrote.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050214.0755"><line>&quot;What I think the fans are most interested in is fixing the problem rather than what has happened in the past.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>&quot;They have left the committee no alternative but to issue subpoenas.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041115.0562"><line>Bonds testified before a grand jury looking into the BALCO steroid scandal and his personal trainer, Greg Anderson, was among four men charged in the case.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>They talk about it.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050224.0679"><line>&quot;This would be an opportunity to find out what really happened and to get to the bottom of this growing scandal.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0624"><line>Caminiti, who played in the major leagues for 15 years, died of an apparent heart attack Sunday at age 41.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="16,19"><scu uid="27" label="Baseball star Ken Caminiti died" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0031"><line>But he struggled to find his place in society once his Major League Baseball playing days ended three years ago.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="48"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041011.0624"><line>Mark McGwire admitted taking andro during a record-breaking 70 home run season in 1998, back when the substance was not banned by the US baseball league, which only began steroid testing of players this season.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="4" sums="10,12,20,42"><scu uid="5" label="Major League Baseball player Mark McGwire admitted taking steroids" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0808"><line>&quot;I can reach no conclusion but that the league and the players' union have misrepresented to me and to the American public the substance of MLB's new steroid policy,&quot; McCain wrote.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line><line>Despite tough talk, baseball's policy shows possible fines with no bans for any steroid offender.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050309.0764"><line>It should not be about poutting people in jail.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050305.0110"><line>In 1998, Selig convened a group at his Milwaukee office, including team physicians, trainers and outside medical experts, and they decided to begin an investigation and to gather as much information about steroid use and its effects as possible.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050316.0808"><line>To do anything less than that would constitute a violation of the public's trust, a blow to the integrity of Major League Baseball and an invitation to further scrutiny of the league's steroid policy.&quot;</line></document></collection>